The newly inaugurated board of the Nigeria National Accreditation System (NiNAS) has underscored the importance of accreditation in national development, saying Nigeria can maximally reap the proceeds of the newly signed African Continental Free Trade Agreement with good laid down structure. The new board chairman, Hajiya Saratu Aliyu, made this known during the official inauguration of the NiNAS board yesterday in Abuja, saying accreditation would ensure standardisation which means that products coming from Nigeria stands at par with its counterparts globally. “I know the importance of accreditation. So, NINAS accrediting organisations will make the standards of what we do in Nigeria to be at a very high level and people all over the world will recognise us because they know we are accredited,” she said. Aliyu also promised that the new board would commence a nationwide sensitisation to educate Nigerians on the importance of accrediting their products, services and organisations, adding that accreditation which is free of charge will boost the standard of Nigerian products globally. In his remarks, the director-general of NiNAS, Celestine Okanya, said the reason for accreditation was not for the companies or organisations but for consumers, adding that the quality of almost every consumable cannot be guaranteed without accreditation. He explained that the job of NiNAS is to stand in the gap in making sure regulators follow due process in carrying out their regulatory functions. “Yes, we have a standard body that sets the standard for everything. We have a very good standard body in our country. But when SON sets the standard, they need companies to follow the standard and for companies to comply with the standard they have to follow what the standard says. Therefore, you need an independent body to provide evidence that they are following what they say,”he said. 